The paper discusses the use of memristors as a route to neuromorphic computing, which falls under the category of computational neuroscience (cs.NE). The paper also discusses the physical rules governing the interaction of current spikes in memristors, which could fall under the category of electronic devices and circuits (cs.ET). The paper also introduces logical systems to implement sequential logic in memristors, which could fall under the category of computer architecture (cs.AR). The paper also discusses the use of plastic rewritable connections between spiking logic gates, which could fall under the category of electronic and photonic devices (cs.ETL). Finally, the paper demonstrates the implementation of a Full Adder with a single memristor, which could fall under the category of logic in computer science (cs.LG).
